  <p>
    A drain field rarely fails all at once. It sends signals for weeks or months first — and because
    the field is underground, those signals show up at the surface, in the ground above it. Every one
    of them is a chance to act while the problem is still small. The owners who end up replacing a
    field are almost always the ones who waited; the ones who catch it early often have far cheaper
    options.
  </p>

